prefix: Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in mathematics would.
problem_prompt:
Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in mathematics would. The values of a function $f(x)$ are given below:

\begin{tabular}{|c||c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 \\ \hline $f(x)$ & 10 & 17 & 26 & 37 & 50 \\ \hline \end{tabular}Evaluate $f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}(50)\times f^{-1}(10)+f^{-1}(26)\right)$.
solution_prompt:
Yes or no, is the final solution obtained in the following equal to 5?: To evaluate $f^{-1}(50)$, we first note that $f(7)=50$, so $f^{-1}(50)=7$.

Next, to find $f^{-1}(10)$, we note that $f(3)=10$, so $f^{-1}(10)=3$.

Finally, to find $f^{-1}(26)$, we see that $f(5)=26$, so $f^{-1}(26)=5$.

Therefore, $f^{-1}(f^{-1}(50)\times f^{-1}(10)+f^{-1}(26))=f^{-1}(7\times 3+5)=f^{-1}(21+5)=f^{-1}(26)=\boxed{5}$.
